title: Z-touch: a multi-touch platform using finger posture
title_en: Z-touch: a multi-touch platform using finger posture
abstract: 本研究は指の姿勢情報を利用するマルチタッチ入力プラットフォームを提示しており、指の姿勢検出によりタッチ入力の表現力と種類の識別を向上させることを目的としています。 本研究は複数の光平面と高フレームレート撮像を組み合わせて指をHigh／Middle／Lowの3段階に分類し、200fpsでリアルタイムに指姿勢ベースのマルチタッチ検出を行う技術を示しています。
abstract_en: This research presents a multi-touch input platform that uses finger posture information to enhance the expressiveness and distinguishability of touch inputs. This research combines multiple light planes and high-frame-rate imaging to classify fingers into three levels (High/Middle/Low) and performs real-time posture-based multi-touch detection at 200 fps.
positioning_summary: 本研究は指の姿勢情報を用いるマルチタッチプラットフォームを提案しており、マルチタッチ入力が指位置中心で姿勢情報を扱わないという既存の欠落を埋める点を中心的な位置づけとしています。 本研究は従来の光学や力覚に基づく手法が持つ制約を克服して指の高さや姿勢を識別することを目的としており、マルチタッチ利用者やインタフェース設計者を主な対象としています。
positioning_summary_en: This research positions itself as a multi-touch platform that uses finger posture information to fill the gap where traditional multi-touch treats only finger positions and not posture. This research aims to overcome limitations of conventional optical and force-based methods by identifying finger height and posture, targeting multi-touch users and interface designers.
purpose_summary: 本研究の目的は指の姿勢や深度情報を取得してマルチタッチ入力の表現力と認識精度を向上させることです。 本研究はフレーム間で検出されたタッチ用ブロブを正しくマッチングして指の姿勢を推定し、マルチタッチにおけるタッチの曖昧さと識別誤りを低減することを具体的な目標としています。
purpose_summary_en: The purpose of this research is to obtain finger posture and depth information to improve the expressiveness and recognition accuracy of multi-touch input. This research specifically aims to reduce touch ambiguity and recognition errors by correctly matching detected touch blobs across frames and estimating finger posture.
method_summary: 本システムは複数の光平面を用いるレーザ光平面方式の拡張と高フレームレート撮像を組み合わせて、指をHigh／Middle／Lowの3段階に分類することで指姿勢ベースのマルチタッチ検出を実現しています。 本システムはVGA相当の200fpsカメラとBlobheightや形状類似度 s(a;b)、距離 d(a;b) を組み合わせたコスト関数 c(a;b)＝{s(a;b)/k + d(a;b) if d<T, 1 otherwise} によるブロブマッチングを用い、約1m角や約0.6m×0.6mの試作面上で処理を行っています。
method_summary_en: This system extends a laser light-plane approach by using multiple light planes combined with high-frame-rate imaging to classify finger posture into three levels (High/Middle/Low) for posture-based multi-touch detection. This system uses a VGA-equivalent 200 fps camera and blob matching with Blobheight and a cost function combining shape similarity s(a;b) and distance d(a;b) with threshold T and weight k, and it runs on prototypes roughly 1 m square and 0.6 m by 0.6 m.
evaluation_summary: 本研究は約1m角と約0.6m×0.6mの試作面で動作検証を行い、層間隔約40mmでの3段階高さ分類と200fpsでのリアルタイム検出が可能かを評価しました。 本研究は試作ハードウェア上での動作確認として3段階高さ分類が可能であることと200fpsでの検出が実現できたことを報告し、3DCG操作実験の条件下で本システムが3DCG操作に有効であることを示唆しました。
evaluation_summary_en: This research evaluated operation on prototype surfaces approximately 1 m square and 0.6 m by 0.6 m to assess whether three-level height classification with inter-layer spacing around 40 mm and real-time detection at 200 fps is achievable. This research reported that three-level height classification was possible and that detection at 200 fps was achieved on prototype hardware, and it suggested effectiveness for 3D graphics manipulation under evaluated conditions.

Paper summary:
Title: Z-touch: a multi-touch platform using finger posture
Authors: Yoshiki Takeoka, Takashi Miyaki, Jun Rekimoto
Year: 2010
Abstract: This research presents a multi-touch input platform that uses finger posture information to enhance the expressiveness and distinguishability of touch inputs. This research combines multiple light planes and high-frame-rate imaging to classify fingers into three levels (High/Middle/Low) and performs real-time posture-based multi-touch detection at 200 fps.
Positioning Summary: This research positions itself as a multi-touch platform that uses finger posture information to fill the gap where traditional multi-touch treats only finger positions and not posture. This research aims to overcome limitations of conventional optical and force-based methods by identifying finger height and posture, targeting multi-touch users and interface designers.
Purpose Summary: The purpose of this research is to obtain finger posture and depth information to improve the expressiveness and recognition accuracy of multi-touch input. This research specifically aims to reduce touch ambiguity and recognition errors by correctly matching detected touch blobs across frames and estimating finger posture.
Method Summary: This system extends a laser light-plane approach by using multiple light planes combined with high-frame-rate imaging to classify finger posture into three levels (High/Middle/Low) for posture-based multi-touch detection. This system uses a VGA-equivalent 200 fps camera and blob matching with Blobheight and a cost function combining shape similarity s(a;b) and distance d(a;b) with threshold T and weight k, and it runs on prototypes roughly 1 m square and 0.6 m by 0.6 m.
Evaluation Summary: This research evaluated operation on prototype surfaces approximately 1 m square and 0.6 m by 0.6 m to assess whether three-level height classification with inter-layer spacing around 40 mm and real-time detection at 200 fps is achievable. This research reported that three-level height classification was possible and that detection at 200 fps was achieved on prototype hardware, and it suggested effectiveness for 3D graphics manipulation under evaluated conditions.
